<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="33">
(modified from 
<bibRefCitation author="Danielopol, DL" journalOrPublisher="Biologia Gallo-Hellenica" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" pagination="99 - 107" refId="B17" refString="Danielopol, DL, 1979. On the origin and the antiquity of the Pseudolimnocythere species (Ostracoda, Loxoconchidae). Biologia Gallo-Hellenica 8: 99 - 107" title="On the origin and the antiquity of the Pseudolimnocythere species (Ostracoda, Loxoconchidae)." volume="8" year="1979">Danielopol 1979</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-21810-1" author="Karanovic, I" journalOrPublisher="Springer, Berlin Heidelberg" pageId="0" pageNumber="33" refId="B36" refString="Karanovic, I, 2012. Recent Freshwater Ostracods of the World. Crustacea, Ostracoda, Podocopida. Springer, Berlin Heidelberg, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-21810-1" title="Recent Freshwater Ostracods of the World. Crustacea, Ostracoda, Podocopida" url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-21810-1" year="2012">Karanovic 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Small ostracods (length &lt;0.4 mm), without sexual dimorphism. Carapace ornamented with rounded pits. Hinge henodont (single posterior tooth in RV), invicidont, or amphidont. Calcified inner lamella wide, marginal pore canals branched; normal pore canals with small sieve plates located in deep funnels. Antennula, six-segmented (fourth and fifth segments only partially separated or completely indistinct), the distal segment exceeding the length of the second segment. Exopod of antenna not segmented; penultimate segment with two basal setae and one aesthetasc, and two distal (anterior) setae.
</paragraph>
